1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Stanford University

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Okay, the question arose about the paradox of

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:24,000
if two particles, both fermions, make up a boson,

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,000
can we have a boson, two bosons,

5
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
which are, let's say, in the same state?

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Perhaps a more general question.

7
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:43,000
The wave function of bosons is supposed to be symmetric

8
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,000
on the interchange of the two bosons.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,000
That means, for example, if you had two bosons

10
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:50,500
and the wave function describing them was

11
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:53,000
a function of, let's say, x and y,

12
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,000
this doesn't mean the two bosons are the same.

13
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:56,500
This means that if you're using two coordinates,

14
00:00:56,500 --> 00:00:59,000
x and y, in the x and y direction,

15
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:01,500
x and y are simply now standing

16
00:01:01,500 --> 00:01:04,000
for particle number 1 and particle number 2.

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
If they're bosons, then the rule is that

18
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
that must equal psi of y and x.

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,000
That's another way of saying you

20
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,000
can't distinguish between the two particles.

21
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,500
There's no difference between saying

22
00:01:19,500 --> 00:01:23,000
you have a two boson system

23
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:23,500
in the state psi of x and y,

24
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:24,000
and saying you can distinguish between the two bosons.

25
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,500
You have two bosons in the

26
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:27,000
state psi of y and x.

27
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,000
It's interchange symmetric between them.

28
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And in that case, you can certainly

29
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:36,000
have two particles in the same state.

30
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:39,000
For example, a special case of this

31
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
would be that psi is a product function.

32
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:44,500
Psi of x and y is a product of,

33
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:47,000
I don't want to use the label psi again,

34
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,000
because I've used psi to label two particle wave functions,

35
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:52,000
but let's invent another thing

36
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:53,000
to describe one particle wave function.

37
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Let's just call it phi.

38
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,500
And psi of x and y could

39
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:01,000
be phi of x times phi of y.

40
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,500
This would correspond to a boson

41
00:02:05,500 --> 00:02:10,000
with two bosons with wave function phi,

42
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
with the same wave function.

43
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
In other words, in the same quantum state.

44
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,000
That's what this would mean, a two particle state,

45
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:22,000
and each particle is in the state phi.

46
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,000
So, the cross is obviously symmetric.

47
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
It is the same as phi of y and

48
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:33,000
x, sorry, phi of y times phi of x.

49
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Wave functions are not operators.

50
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:36,000
They commute.

51
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Wave functions are just ordinary numbers.

52
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
They're not matrices.

53
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:42,000
They're just functions of x,

54
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,500
and they satisfy all of the

55
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:47,000
algebraic properties of perfectly ordinary functions.

56
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And so, what did I write?

57
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Yeah, I wrote the right thing.

58
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
Yes, two bosons can be in the same state,

59
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
and the wave function be symmetric.

60
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,000
What about two fermions?

61
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,500
The rule for two fermions, if we

62
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:04,000
put them, if we have two fermions,

63
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
is that the wave function has to change sign.

64
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Now, that's a very odd thing, but nevertheless,

65
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,500
that is the mathematical rule,

66
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:18,000
the abstract mathematical rule for fermions.

67
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
When you interchange them, the

68
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
sign of the wave function changes.

69
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Now, okay, so that's the difference between them.

70
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Then, can you have two fermions in the same state?

71
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,500
No, because phi of x and y is

72
00:03:32,500 --> 00:03:35,000
not equal to minus phi of y and y.

73
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:36,000
You see what I mean.

74
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Phi of x times phi of y is not equal to

75
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,000
phi of y and phi of x with a minus sign.

76
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:51,000
All right, now, supposing I have a wave function

77
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
for two particles.

78
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,500
Can I make, and it's

79
00:03:55,500 --> 00:03:58,000
not symmetric and it's not anti-symmetric,

80
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
can I make something out of it which is symmetric

81
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
or something which is anti-symmetric?

82
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
So let me show you how you do that.

83
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,500
Supposing I had some wave function

84
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:12,000
which was neither symmetric nor anti-symmetric.

85
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Let's just call it phi of x and y.

86
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:20,000
When you interchange x and y, it neither changes sign,

87
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
nor does it stay the same.

88
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,000
So it's neither symmetric nor anti-symmetric.

89
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
All right, if you want to make something symmetric,

90
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:33,000
which is an appropriate wave function for two bosons,

91
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
you just add

92
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,000
phi of y and x.

93
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Now this is obviously symmetric.

94
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
If you interchange x and y,

95
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:47,000
this one becomes this one, this one becomes this one,

96
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
and nothing happens to that.

97
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Now this is a symmetric wave function.

98
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
This is a possible wave function for

99
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
bosons for any psi of x and y.

100
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And if we're talking about fermions,

101
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
we can do the same thing,

102
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
except that we put a minus sign there.

103
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
Now what happens if we interchange x and y?

104
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:10,500
This one goes to this one,

105
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:12,000
this one goes to this one,

106
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
but the whole thing will change sign.

107
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
The whole thing will change sign

108
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
if we interchange x and y.

109
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:20,000
Okay.

110
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
So this is a wave function for fermions.

111
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Symmetrized is called symmetrizing and anti-symmetrizing,

112
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
a wave function for two particles.

113
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Okay, now let's suppose we have four particles altogether.

114
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,000
Four fermions.

115
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Four fermions, what are the rules for four fermions?

116
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
And for simplicity, let's suppose there

117
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
are two different kinds of fermions.

118
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Let's say there is electrons and protons,

119
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
but we're talking about hydrogen atoms.

120
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:52,500
Now, the rule, okay, so

121
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:54,000
let's see what is the rule.

122
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:58,000
We have a four-body wave function.

123
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Let's now let electrons be called

124
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:04,000
x and protons be called y.

125
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:07,000
So the wave function is a function of two x's,

126
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:16,000
let's call them x1 and x2, y1 and y2.

127
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,000
So a function of four variables.

128
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:26,000
What are the rules?

129
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
The rules are, first of all, that

130
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:30,000
the wave function has to change sign

131
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
if you interchange x1 and x2.

132
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,000
That's the fact that the electrons are fermions.

133
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,500
It must also change sign

134
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:44,000
when you interchange y1 and y2.

135
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Incidentally, let's see.

136
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Let's do this right.

137
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
It must also change sign

138
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
when you interchange y1 and y2.

139
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:03,000
Yeah, that's the rule.

140
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Those are the only rules.

141
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:07,000
Sign change when you interchange x1 and x2,

142
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
that's because electrons are fermions,

143
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:13,000
and a sign change when you interchange y1 and y2

144
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
because protons are fermions.

145
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
So let's see what kind

146
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
of wave functions we can build.

147
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Let's start with a hydrogen atom.

148
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:34,000
A hydrogen atom located at the origin.

149
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,000
A hydrogen atom located at

150
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
the origin has a wave function,

151
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:43,000
which is a function of its electron and its proton.

152
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
So one now picks out

153
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
one of the two hydrogen atoms.

154
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:52,000
One now stands for one of the two hydrogen atoms.

155
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,500
And this might be some wave

156
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:57,000
function governing one of the hydrogen atoms,

157
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,000
over here.

158
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:03,000
But supposing I want to shift its location.

159
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
How would I shift its location?

160
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Well, it's easy to shift its location.

161
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
You just shift the origin of both x1 and x2.

162
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
I guess I don't really have to do it.

163
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Okay.

164
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
I don't need to shift its origin.

165
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
And then we have another pair.

166
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,500
And the other pair is describing

167
00:08:25,500 --> 00:08:29,000
a hydrogen atom at some other location.

168
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
All right.

169
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:34,000
Since it's a hydrogen atom at another location,

170
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,000
it has a different wave function.

171
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
The wave function may be the

172
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:41,000
same except that it's been translated,

173
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,000
but it's not.

174
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
It's been translated, but it is different.

175
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:51,000
Phi of x2 and y2.

176
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:54,000
Now, in general, this is neither

177
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,000
symmetric with respect to the x's

178
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
or anti-symmetric with respect to the x's

179
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:03,000
or, for that matter, with respect to the y's.

180
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:06,000
So it's not a good wave function for fermions.

181
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:08,500
Supposing I want to make it

182
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:11,000
anti-symmetric on the interchange of the electrons.

183
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,000
That's very easy.

184
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:17,000
We just subtract off here

185
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,000
psi of...

186
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:22,000
I just interchange x1 and x2,

187
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,000
leaving y1 and y2 alone.

188
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:26,000
All right.

189
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:28,000
So let's do that first.

190
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Minus psi of x2y1

191
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
phi of x1y2.

192
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:48,000
It is now anti-symmetric with respect to the x's.

193
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:49,500
If I interchange the two

194
00:09:49,500 --> 00:09:51,000
x's, the whole thing changes sign.

195
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
But it's not anti-symmetric with respect to the y's.

196
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Okay.

197
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:56,500
How do I make it

198
00:09:56,500 --> 00:09:58,000
anti-symmetric with respect to the y's?

199
00:09:58,000 --> 00:09:59,500
The answer is take the

200
00:09:59,500 --> 00:10:01,000
whole thing that I have here,

201
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:05,000
interchange the two y's, and put a minus sign in.

202
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:06,000
All right.

203
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:08,000
So we put in minus

204
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,000
psi of x1 and y2.

205
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
phi of x2y2.

206
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,000
That's exactly this with...

207
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,000
Sorry, y1.

208
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,000
This and this are the same, except

209
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
that y2 and y1 have been interchanged.

210
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
And I put a minus sign in.

211
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,000
And then I want to anti-symmetrize this one

212
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:33,000
with respect to the exchange of the y's.

213
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:35,000
So that becomes plus...

214
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,000
I have to change the sign.

215
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:40,000
psi of x2y2.

216
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:45,000
phi of x1y1.

217
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Okay.

218
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
So this is now anti-symmetric with respect

219
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
to both the x's and the y's.

220
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
If you interchange in this expression, x1 and x2,

221
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
it'll go to this one and change sign.

222
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
If you interchange x1 and x2 here,

223
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
this one, and so forth.

224
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,000
The whole thing is fully anti-symmetric.

225
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Fully anti-symmetric, yeah.

226
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:15,000
My problem is if you take those two hydrogen's atoms

227
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:17,000
and put them closer and closer,

228
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:18,500
there's nothing preventing you from doing

229
00:11:18,500 --> 00:11:20,000
that because there are bosons, right?

230
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:23,000
There may be forces between them.

231
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:25,000
There may be...

232
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,000
The Pauli principle does create a

233
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
kind of force between the atoms.

234
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
It will make it very, very...

235
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:37,000
It'll make it essentially impossible

236
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
to put two atoms right on top of each other.

237
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,000
But you'll simply attribute that to a force.

238
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
But will you be able to put

239
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:46,000
two atoms into the same momentum state?

240
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
Momentum states are spread out all over the place.

241
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
They are spread out in space.

242
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,000
So when you put two

243
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,000
atoms into the same momentum state,

244
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:57,000
you're not ramming them in on top of each other,

245
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:00,000
and it doesn't cost a lot of energy.

246
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
So, yeah, the question of whether you can

247
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,000
stick two things on top of each other

248
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:05,500
is a different question than

249
00:12:05,500 --> 00:12:07,000
whether they're fermions and bosons.

250
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:11,000
It can even happen that, you know,

251
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:14,000
billiard balls can be bosons.

252
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:16,000
You can't stick them on top of each other.

253
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:18,000
They have hard cores.

254
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:20,000
Nevertheless, they can be bosons.

255
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,000
You can put them...

256
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:24,000
You can't put them at the same point.

257
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,000
It just costs too much energy,

258
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:28,000
but you can put them into the same momentum.

259
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:33,000
But if your wave functions are eigenvalue...

260
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
Eigenfunctions of momentum,

261
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:36,000
then couldn't you...

262
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:39,000
Couldn't you have the two hydrogen atoms

263
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
in this same eigenstate of momentum,

264
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,500
and then you would have

265
00:12:43,500 --> 00:12:46,000
two fermions in the same state?

266
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:50,000
No. No, no, no, no, no.

267
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,000
Just take any wave function like this.

268
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:54,000
Is this...

269
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:57,000
It's anti-symmetric with exchanges to x.

270
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:00,000
It's anti-symmetric with respect to exchanges of y.

271
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
